::\n<br><br>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n:::: {.panel-tabset .nav-pills}\n\n## Prison Population\n<center>\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n```{=html}\n<div id=\"body-section\">\n<br/>\n<div id=\"big-section-title\">New Court Commits vs. Parole Revocations</div>\n<br/>\n<div id=\"regular-text\">While the public often envisions a prison population primarily made up of individuals serving long sentences for serious crimes, the reality is far more nuanced. In particular, the distinction between new court commits—those incarcerated for the first time on a new charge—and parole revocations—those returned to prison for violating the conditions of their parole—is a critical one. Understanding the proportion of these two groups within the prison population can provide valuable insights into the effectiveness of the state's criminal justice policies, including sentencing and parole practices.</div>\n<br/>\n<div id=\"visualization\">No Data</div>\n<br/>\n</div>\n```\n:::\n:::\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n```{=html}\n<div id=\"body-section\">\n<br/>\n<div id=\"big-section-title\">Prison Population Trends</div>\n<br/>\n<div id=\"visualization\">\n<div id=\"htmlwidget-f257ef25897d531388e3\" style=\"width:100%;height:433px;\" class=\"highchart html-widget \"></div>\n<script type=\"application/json\" data-for=\"htmlwidget-f257ef25897d531388e3\">{\"x\":{\"hc_opts\":{\"chart\":{\"reflow\":true,\"width\":600,\"height\":400},\"title\":{\"text\":\"Trends in Prison Population, Releases to Parole, and Parole Eligibility\"},\"yAxis\":{\"title\":{\"text\":null},\"labels\":{\"format\":\"{value:,.0f}\"}},\"credits\":{\"enabled\":false},\"exporting\":{\"enabled\":true},\"boost\":{\"enabled\":false},\"plotOptions\":{\"series\":{\"label\":{\"enabled\":false},\"turboThreshold\":0},\"treemap\":{\"layoutAlgorithm\":\"squarified\"},\"column\":{\"dataLabels\":{\"enabled\":true}}},\"xAxis\":{\"categories\":[2009,2010,2011,2012,2013,2014,2015,2016,2017,2018,2019,2020],\"labe